
==============================
  STREAM vs PARALLEL STREAM
==============================

Feature        | Stream (Sequential)        | Parallel Stream
---------------------------------------------------------------
Execution      | Sequential processing     | Parallel processing
Threads        | Single thread             | Multiple threads (ForkJoinPool)
Performance    | Slower for large data     | Faster for large datasets (if used properly)
Order          | Maintains order           | May not maintain order
Use Case       | Small / Medium data       | Large data processing

---------------------------------------------------------------
NOTES:
- Stream processes elements one by one.
- Parallel Stream splits data into multiple parts and processes simultaneously.
- Use parallelStream() method to create parallel stream.
- Not always faster — depends on CPU cores and task complexity.
- Avoid parallel stream when order is important or for small datasets.

---------------------------------------------------------------
EXAMPLE:

// Sequential Stream
list.stream()
    .forEach(System.out::println);

// Parallel Stream
list.parallelStream()
    .forEach(System.out::println);

---------------------------------------------------------------


✅ 🔹 Stream (Sequential) – Internal Working


💡 Flow:
Collection → converted to Stream
Uses Spliterator to iterate elements
Operations form a pipeline
Intermediate: filter(), map()
Terminal: forEach(), collect()
Execution happens sequentially (one by one)


🎯 Interview Line:

“Stream internally uses Spliterator and processes data 
sequentially using a single thread with a pipeline of operations.”






✅ 🔹 Parallel Stream – Internal Working


💡 Flow:
Data is split into multiple parts using Spliterator
Tasks are submitted to ForkJoinPool.commonPool()
Multiple threads process chunks in parallel
Results are combined (merge phase)



🎯 Interview Line:

“Parallel stream internally uses Spliterator to divide 
data and ForkJoinPool 
to process tasks in parallel using multiple threads.”



//Combined Answer 

🎯 🔹 Final Best Answer (Say This)

“Sequential stream internally uses Spliterator to 
iterate elements and processes them in 
a single thread using a pipeline of operations. 
